  "runtimeMin": 87,
  "format": "Sean, Amanda, and Ringerverse chief Mallory Rubin cover Phase 5's opener: Kang, MODOK, and whether the multiverse can still land, capped by the first Amanda's Science Corner.",
  "segments": [
    {
      "kind": "review",
      "heading": "‘Ant-Man and the Wasp: Quantumania’",
      "note": "the review",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Ant-Man and the Wasp: Quantumania",
          "year": 2023,
          "note": "Phase 5's opener, spent almost entirely in the quantum realm. Sean liked it, Amanda had no idea what happened but laughed a lot, and Mallory came away mixed: she thinks the CGI setting drained the heart the first two Ant-Man films ran on. Jonathan Majors' Kang and a Corey Stoll MODOK get the most love; the Baskin-Robbins framing and Michael Douglas' Hank Pym close behind."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "discussion",
      "heading": "Is Marvel's future here too?",
      "note": "the state of the MCU",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Spider-Man: No Way Home",
          "year": 2021,
          "note": "The last MCU film to clear a billion dollars, the yardstick everything since has fallen short of."
        },
        {
          "title": "Doctor Strange in the Multiverse of Madness",
          "year": 2022,
          "note": "Hugely hyped, never broke a billion; cited as the multiverse-fatigue warning sign."
        },
        {
          "title": "Black Panther: Wakanda Forever",
          "year": 2022,
          "note": "Mallory rates it well above Quantumania; different aims entirely, she argues, so not a fair comp."
        },
        {
          "title": "Guardians of the Galaxy Vol. 3",
          "year": 2023,
          "note": "Due in May; the one film on the slate nobody at the table doubts."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Marvels",
          "year": 2023,
          "note": "The July release that closes out Marvel's year, with no dated TV shows behind it."
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
